<paragraph blockId="6.[130,777,1261,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
PHENOLOGY. — The flowering period of 
<taxonomicName authority="Eroğlu, 2022" authorityName="Eroğlu" authorityYear="2022" box="[542,694,1939,1963]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Asperula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fidanii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[542,694,1939,1963]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Asperula fidanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[701,777,1939,1962]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is between July and September, the fruiting time is August and September.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="203" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1013,1630]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
DISTRIBUTION AND ECOLOGY. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Eroğlu, 2022" authorityName="Eroğlu" authorityYear="2022" box="[1130,1276,1013,1037]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Asperula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fidanii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1130,1276,1013,1037]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Asperula fidanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1278,1350,1013,1036]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is endemic to ŞIrnak-Turkey. It spreads on cracks in limestone cliffs habitats at elevation of 
<quantity box="[925,1060,1066,1090]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="m" value="1400.0" valueMax="1500.0" valueMin="1300.0">1300-1500 m</quantity>
. It is a native species of the Irano-Turanian floristic region (
<figureCitation box="[968,1024,1092,1116]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-62@10.[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 6. — Habitat of Asperula fidanii Eroğlu, sp. nov.: A, general view; B, close view. Note: the white arrows in the photo A show the spots on the rock where the species was present." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6817842" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6817842/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="203" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1013,1630]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
ETYMOLOGY. — This new species was named 
<taxonomicName authority="Eroğlu, 2022" authorityName="Eroğlu" authorityYear="2022" box="[1235,1379,1140,1164]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Asperula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fidanii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1235,1379,1140,1164]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Asperula fidanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1383,1455,1140,1163]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in order to honor Yusuf Fidan, who participated in the fieldwork with the author at the time the species was first collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1013,1630]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
PALYNOLOGICAL PROPERTIES. — The pollen grains of 
<taxonomicName authority="Eroğlu, 2022" authorityName="Eroğlu" authorityYear="2022" box="[1309,1454,1240,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Asperula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fidanii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1309,1454,1240,1264]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Asperula fidanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[811,885,1267,1290]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are monads, isopolar (5-)6-7 zonocolpate, suboblate [Polar length: 15.43 (± 1.93), Equatorial length: 17.60 (± 1.05), Polar length/Equatorial length: 0.88, Exine thickness: 1.20 (± 0.16), Intine thickness: 0.77 (± 0.06), Colpus length: 9.82 (± 1.08), Colpus width: 1.48 (± 0.40)], ornamentation is sparse-heterogeneous microperforate and scabrate. The average number of scabrae at 1 µm2: 
<quantity box="[813,883,1426,1450]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.429" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="in" value="13.5">13.5 in</quantity>
polar area, 
<quantity box="[997,1068,1426,1450]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2672" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="in" value="16.8">16.8 in</quantity>
equatorial area (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1287,1426,1450]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[132,143,1600,1617]" captionTargetBox="[131,1454,215,1556]" captionTargetId="figure-151@9.[131,1454,214,1556]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 5. — SEM micrographs of pollen grains and mericarp of Asperula fidanii Eroğlu, sp. nov.; A, equatorial view; B, polar view; C, D, close ornamentation and colpus views of pollen grains; E, general view of mericarp; F, close view of mericarp. Scale bars: A, B, 2 µm; C, D, 1 µm; E, 300 µm; F, 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6817840" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6817840/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
A-D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="206" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1013,1630]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
MERICARP SURFACE PROPERTIES. — The mericarp surface has reticulate ornamentation 
<typeStatus box="[1009,1054,1500,1524]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">type</typeStatus>
. Surface cells are polygonal, between 35 and 45 µm in diameter. They have secondary structures like, lineshaped or ruminate cuticular spurs. While the 
<typeStatus box="[1279,1329,1553,1577]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">types</typeStatus>
of anticlinal cell walls in 
<taxonomicName authority="Eroğlu, 2022" authorityName="Eroğlu" authorityYear="2022" box="[927,1076,1579,1603]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Asperula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF,IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fidanii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[927,1076,1579,1603]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Asperula fidanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1080,1154,1580,1603]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are sunken, periclinal cell walls are convex or concave (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1140,1605,1630]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[132,143,1600,1617]" captionTargetBox="[131,1454,215,1556]" captionTargetId="figure-151@9.[131,1454,214,1556]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 5. — SEM micrographs of pollen grains and mericarp of Asperula fidanii Eroğlu, sp. nov.; A, equatorial view; B, polar view; C, D, close ornamentation and colpus views of pollen grains; E, general view of mericarp; F, close view of mericarp. Scale bars: A, B, 2 µm; C, D, 1 µm; E, 300 µm; F, 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6817840" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6817840/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">Fig. 5E, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1683,2028]" box="[813,957,1683,1709]" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1683,2028]" lastBlockId="8.[130,776,1587,1773]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="205" pageId="6" pageNumber="203">
Caespitose and suffruticose perennial. Stems numerous, 
<quantity box="[815,909,1747,1773]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="cm" value="13.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="8.0">8-18 cm</quantity>
, ascending, fragile, quadrangular, setulose. Petioles minute or absent. Leaves 2, opposite, obtuse or acute, with a prominent nerve in lower surface, with semi-revolute margins, stipules absent. Basal leaves ovate-orbicular 1-4 × 
<quantity box="[1357,1450,1842,1869]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="mm" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1-3 mm</quantity>
. Middle and upper leaves ovate-lanceolate to elliptical-lanceolate, 3-21 × (2)4-7(9) mm. Inflorescence lax, dichasial, flowers 1-6, bracts linear-lanceolate to elliptical-lanceolate, setulose, 1-2 × 
<quantity box="[988,1105,1969,1996]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="1.0" valueMin="0.5">0.5-1 mm</quantity>
, bracteoles similar, smaller. Peduncle 
<quantity box="[892,984,2001,2028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2-5 mm</quantity>
. Pedicels minute to 
<quantity box="[1200,1268,2002,2028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="203" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
, with short hairs. Corolla white when fresh, creamy when dry, pubescent, 4- or 5- lobed, tubular, 
<quantity box="[358,467,1619,1646]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.0">2-2.5 mm</quantity>
with lobes, tube longer than lobes, stamens epipetalous, 
<quantity box="[433,581,1651,1678]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.25" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="0.625" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.5">0.5-0.75 mm</quantity>
, 4 or 5. Ovarium 
<emphasis box="[134,150,1683,1708]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="205">c.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[153,218,1683,1709]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
, oblong, glabrous, styles 2, 
<emphasis box="[500,517,1683,1708]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="205">c.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[523,608,1682,1709]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
, not permanent on fruit, stigma globose. Mericarp broadly ovate-orbicular to orbicular, glabrous, 
<quantity box="[345,458,1746,1773]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="205" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5-2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
